The '''Ground Combat Vehicle''' ('''GCV''') was a program initiated by the [[United States Army]] in 2009, with the goal of developing a next-generation [[armored fighting vehicle]]. The first variant of the GCV to be developed would be an [[infantry fighting vehicle]] to replace the [[M2 Bradley]].

The program was intended to provide increased protection and firepower for ground troops, with a focus on improved crew survivability. The Army planned on acquiring 1,874 GCV infantry fighting vehicles to replace Bradleys in 16 active and 8 [[Army National Guard|National Guard]] [[Brigade Combat Team#Armored Brigade Combat Team|Heavy Brigade Combat Teams]]. In 2011, the Army selected [[BAE Systems]] and [[General Dynamics Land Systems]] to move forward with the GCV program.

The program faced significant challenges from the start, including limited funding and concerns about the weight of the vehicle. The GCV was designed to be heavily armored and to transport a fully equipped [[squad]] of nine soldiers, something the Bradley could not do. This requirement necessitated adding significant weight to the vehicle, making it less mobile.

The Army canceled the GCV program in 2014 due to the service's budget constraints. The cancellation of the GCV program marked a setback for the U.S. Army, which had been looking to modernize its armored fighting vehicle fleet for many years. The [[Department of Defense]] had canceled the Army's previous combat vehicle program, [[Future Combat Systems]] [[Future Combat Systems Manned Ground Vehicles|Manned Ground Vehicles]] in 2009.

After the cancelation of the GCV program, the U.S. Army shifted its focus to upgrading its existing fleet of [[Bradley Fighting Vehicles]]. Canceling the GCV freed up Army development resources to proceed with the [[Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle]] (AMPV), the service's replacement for the [[M113 armored personnel carrier]] family. The Army has embarked on a comprehensive combat vehicle acquisition effort called [[Next Generation Combat Vehicle]], which includes AMPV within its scope. In 2018 the Army established what came to be known as the [[Optionally Manned Fighting Vehicle]] program, the modern successor to the GCV infantry fighting vehicle effort.<ref name="defensenews6april14">{{cite news |last1=McCleary |first1=Paul |title=US Army, Marines Struggle With Infantry Vehicle Replacements |url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140406/DEFREG02/304060009/US-Army-Marines-Struggle-Infantry-Vehicle-Replacements |access-date=12 May 2024 |work=Defense News |publisher=Gannett |archive-url=https://archive.today/20140823190952/http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140406/DEFREG02/304060009/US-Army-Marines-Struggle-Infantry-Vehicle-Replacements|archive-date=23 August 2014 }}</ref>

==Development==
===Background===
The [[U.S. Army]]'s [[M2 Bradley]] [[infantry fighting vehicle]] entered service in 1983.{{sfn|Foss|2011|p=458–464}} Although production ended in 1995,{{sfn|Hunnicutt|2015|p=298}} it was upgraded numerous times over the years.{{sfn|Foss|2011|p=458–464}}

The U.S. Army's efforts to develop a successor to the Bradley began in the mid-1980s under the [[Armored Systems Modernization]] program. The Army studied a family of vehicles utilizing common components. A heavy chassis variant would replace vehicles ranging from howitzers, [[main battle tanks]] and Bradleys. This effort was canceled in 1992 due to the collapse of the Soviet Union.<ref name="629 mil">{{cite news |last1=Schafer |first1=Susanne M. |title=Army drops contracts for armored vehicles |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/366666360/?terms=%22Armored%20Systems%20Modernization%22&match=1 |access-date=18 November 2021 |work=Austin American-Statesman |agency=Associated Press |date=9 October 1992}}</ref>

The post–Cold War period saw the Army begin to realize the importance of deploying globally on short notice to small-scale contingencies. In 2000 [[U.S. Army Chief of Staff]] General [[Eric Shinseki]] laid out his vision for a lighter, more transportable force. He called for a mid-weight unit that would strike a balance between heavy armor and infantry. Shinseki said such a unit would be geared toward for [[Military operations other than war (US)|operations short of war]]. The Army was to do this by investing in an interim fleet that would herald the way to a much more advanced subsequent generation of vehicles.<ref name="Vision">{{cite news |last1=MacRae |first1=Catherine |title=Service Wants to Be Lighter, Faster, More Lethal: Army Chief of Staff's 'vision' Is Focused on Medium-weight Force |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/43995956 |access-date=7 February 2022 |work=Inside the Army |issue=41 |publisher=Inside Washington Publishers |date=14 October 1999 |volume=15 |page=6|jstor=43995956 }}</ref> The Army initiated the [[Interim Armored Vehicle]] program that year. The resulting [[Stryker]] wheeled combat vehicle family entered service in 2002.{{sfn|Pernin|Axelband|Drezner|Dille|2012|p=24}}

The Army initiated the [[Future Combat Systems]] (FCS) program in 2000.{{sfn|Pernin|Axelband|Drezner|Dille|2012|p=69}} The combat vehicle component of FCS was the [[FCS Manned Ground Vehicles|Manned Ground Vehicles]] program, a family of eight vehicles including an IFV. By substituting [[active protection system]]s for armor, the Army sought to reduce the weight of a Manned Ground Vehicle to 20 tons, with transportability by [[C-130]] being the limiting factor. This weight requirement proved difficult to meet. Weight at full combat capability (FCC) had risen to 27 tons by January 2007.{{sfn|Pernin|Axelband|Drezner|Dille|2012|p=95-118}}

===Initial program===
[[File:BCT Ground Combat Vehicle industry day 2.jpg|thumb|right|[[Vice Chief of Staff of the U.S. Army]] General [[Peter W. Chiarelli|Peter Chiarelli]] hosts the second industry day.]]

[[Secretary of Defense]] [[Robert Gates]] announced his intention of halting funding for the FCS in April 2009.<ref>{{cite web|title=McHugh nervous about changes|url=http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20090410/NEWS02/304109961|publisher=Watertown Daily Times|access-date=9 August 2010|author=Marc Heller|date=10 April 2009|archive-date=22 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120322012341/http://www.watertowndailytimes.com/article/20090410/NEWS02/304109961|url-status=dead}}</ref> In May, Army and [[Department of Defense]] representatives outlined plans for the cancellation of Future Combat Systems and the initiation of the Ground Combat Vehicle program in its place.<ref name="28 May 2009">{{cite web|title=US Army outlines how it will 'devolve' FCS|url=http://www.janes.com/news/defence/jdw/jdw090528_1_n.shtml|publisher=IHS Global Limited|access-date=9 August 2010|author=Daniel Wasserbly|date=28 May 2009}}</ref>

In June 2009, a [[blue-ribbon panel]] met in Washington D.C. to determine the requirements for the Ground Combat Vehicle.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cavallaro |first=Gina |date=11 June 2009 |title=Panel to Discuss New Ground Combat Vehicle |url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2009/06/army_ground_combat_vehicle_061109w/ |access-date=14 December 2009 |website=Army Times}}</ref> It was concluded at this meeting that an infantry fighting vehicle (IFV) was to be the first vehicle variant fielded.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. Army Details Ground Combat Vehicle Plans|url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4271063|work=Army Times |access-date=20 August 2010|author=Matthew Cox|date=10 June 2009}}{{dead link|date=August 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Later that month, FCS was formally dissolved and many programs including the Manned Ground Vehicle program were canceled with it.<ref>{{Citation |last = Office of the Assistant Secretary of Defense (Public Affairs) |title = Future Combat System (FCS) Program Transitions to Army Brigade Combat Team Modernization |newspaper = [[United States Department of Defense]] |date = 23 June 2009 |url = http://www.defenselink.mil/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=12763 |access-date = 13 November 2013 |archive-date = 1 December 2009 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20091201003318/http://www.defenselink.mil/releases/release.aspx?releaseid=12763 |url-status = dead }}</ref>

In October and November 2009, the Army held informational sessions for potential GCV contractors.<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 2009 |title=U.S. Army Announces Ground Combat Vehicle Industry Day |url=http://www.bctmod.army.mil/news/pdf/GCV_Industry_Day.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430044617/http://www.bctmod.army.mil/news/pdf/GCV_Industry_Day.pdf |archive-date=30 April 2011 |website=United States Army |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Nelson |first=Margaret |date=25 November 2009 |title=U.S. Army Meets with Industry Representatives to Conceive a Ground Combat Vehicle |url=https://www.army.mil/article/31026/us-army-meets-with-industry-representatives-to-conceive-a-ground-combat-vehicle |website=United States Army |access-date=25 November 2009 |archive-date=2 December 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091202080242/http://www.army.mil/-news/2009/11/25/31026-us-army-meets-with-industry-representatives-to-conceive-a-ground-combat-vehicle/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Also that month, Program Executive Office Integration was established to oversee subsystems of [[BCT modernization|BCT Modernization]] including the GCV.<ref>{{cite web|title=Army Establishes Program Executive Office Integration to Support Modernization|url=https://www.army.mil/article/28280/army-establishes-program-executive-office-integration-to-support-modernization/|access-date=11 August 2010|author=Jimmie Cummings|date=2 October 2009|archive-date=20 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100420055840/http://www.army.mil/-news/2009/10/02/28280-army-establishes-program-executive-office-integration-to-support-modernization/|url-status=live}}</ref> A required review was held and passed in February 2010 in Washington.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brannen |first=Kate |date=11 February 2010 |title=DoD Postpones Ground Combat Vehicle Review |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4494373&c=AME&s=LAN |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120729031250/http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4494373&c=AME&s=LAN |archive-date=29 July 2012 |access-date=11 February 2010 |website=[[Defense News]] }}</ref><ref name="Kate">{{Cite web |last=Brannen |first=Kate |date=25 February 2010 |title=Army to Issue Ground Combat Vehicle RfP Today |url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2010/02/defense_army_gcv_rfp_022510w/ |access-date=25 February 2010 |website=[[Defense News]] }}</ref> The GCV [[request for proposal]]s (RFP) was issued in February 2010.<ref name=Kate/> It was revealed in the RfP that the GCV would be a [[cost-plus contract]].<ref name="Brannen RfP">{{cite web|title=Army launches Ground Combat Vehicle contest|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2010/02/army_dn022610_GCV_web/|work=Army Times |access-date=1 October 2010|last=Brannen |first=Kate|date=26 February 2010}}</ref>

By the May deadline, four proposals were submitted.<ref name="ADVS">{{cite web|title=U.S. Army GCV Protest Not Expected to Cause Delay|url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4679299&c=AME&s=LAN|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130121140948/http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4679299&c=AME&s=LAN|url-status=dead|archive-date=January 21, 2013|work=Army Times |access-date=23 June 2010|last=Brannen |first=Kate}}</ref>

In July, management of the GCV was transferred from PEO Integration to PEO Ground Combat Systems with Andrew DiMarco as [[project manager]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/news/2010/07/mil-100727-arnews05.htm|title=The future of ground combat vehicles resides with PEO Ground Combat Systems|publisher=GlobalSecurity.org|access-date=11 August 2010|author=Lori Grein|date=July 27, 2010|archive-date=3 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103193252/http://www.globalsecurity.org/military/library/news/2010/07/mil-100727-arnews05.htm|url-status=live}}</ref> In May, a team was formed to expedite the GCV's seven-year development time.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brannen |first=Kate |date=10 May 2010 |title=Experts Study U.S. Army's GCV Plans, Schedule |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4619649&c=AME&s=LAN |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130121120527/http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4619649&c=AME&s=LAN |archive-date=21 January 2013 |access-date=11 May 2010 |website=Defense News }}</ref> For fiscal year 2011, the U.S. Army sought to spend $934 million of the $2.5 billion allocated for BCT Modernization to develop the GCV.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Cox |first=Matthew |date=1 February 2010 |title=No More Humvees in 2011 Procurement Plan |url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2010/02/army_procurement_020110w/ |access-date=2 February 2010 |website=Army Times}}</ref>

Up to three competitive contracts were to be awarded by early fall.<ref name=IFVspecs/><ref>{{Cite web |last=Scutro |first=Andrew |date=10 January 2010 |title=Army Vague on New Ground Combat Vehicle |url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2010/01/army_vehicle_010910w/ |access-date=26 January 2009 |website=Army Times}}</ref> A prototype development contract decision would have followed by 2013.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Halcom |first=Chad |date=7 February 2010 |title=Budget cuts for vehicles hit defense contractors |url=http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20100207/SUB01/302079979/1069 |access-date=8 February 2010 |publisher=Crain Communications Inc |archive-date=14 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230114030133/https://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20100207/SUB01/302079979/budget-cuts-for-vehicles-hit-defense-contractors |url-status=live }}</ref> The Technology Development Phase (or Milestone A) would begin in the fourth quarter of Fiscal Year 2010 with the award of up to three vehicle contracts. This was to be followed by an Engineering & Manufacturing Development (EMD) phase and [[Low rate initial production|Low Rate Initial Production]] (LRIP) phase before full production could start.<ref name="GCV PROGRAM PLAN"/>

Nine vehicles were evaluated in the Army's 2011 [[Analysis of Alternatives]] (AOA) for the GCV. The four primary vehicles included in the AOA were the [[M2 Bradley#M2A3|M2A3 Bradley]] II, a modernized Stryker, an M2A3 Bradley variant used in Iraq, and a XM1230 [[BAE Caiman|Caiman]] Plus MRAP. The five secondary vehicles included two unnamed foreign-made platforms, the [[M1126 infantry carrier vehicle|M1126 Stryker]] IFV, the [[M1 Abrams#Variants and upgrades|M1A2 SEP TUSK Abrams]] [[main battle tank]], and a modernized M1 Abrams. Vehicles included the AOA were determined to be inferior to the planned GCV.<ref name="AoA">{{Cite web |date=January 2010 |title=Army Evaluated Nine Vehicles Against GCV In Analysis Of Alternatives |url=http://defensenewsstand.com/Inside-Defense-General/Insider/menu-id-286.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100928003142/http://defensenewsstand.com/Inside-Defense-General/Insider/menu-id-286.html |archive-date=28 September 2010 |access-date=12 January 2011 |publisher=Inside Washington Publisher |df=dmy-all}}</ref>

In August 2010 the Army retracted its request for proposals after the team assembled in May recommended that the Army either upgrade the existing ground vehicle fleet or rewrite the requirements.<ref name="delay">{{cite web|title=Army delays Ground Combat Vehicle|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2010/08/DN_army-army-delays-gcv-082510/|work=Army Times |access-date=26 August 2010|first1=John T.|last1=Bennett|last2=Brannen |first2=Kate|date=26 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Bennett |first=John T. |date=25 August 2010 |title=U.S. Army Delays Ground Combat Vehicle |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4677012 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120730101842/http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4677012 |archive-date=30 July 2012 |access-date=20 September 2010 |website=Defense News }}</ref> A new RFP was to be issued 60 days later.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Brannen |first=Kate |date=27 August 2010 |title=U.S. Army's GCV Delay: Lesson Unlearned? |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4757536 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120730110452/http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4757536 |archive-date=30 July 2012 |access-date=20 September 2010 |website=Defense News }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Brannen |first=Kate |date=6 September 2010 |title=Malcolm O'Neill, Acquisition Executive, U.S. Army |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4767908 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120723204335/http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4767908 |archive-date=23 July 2012 |access-date=20 September 2010 |website=Defense News }}</ref> When [[Vice Chief of Staff of the United States Army]] [[Peter W. Chiarelli|Peter Chiarelli]] was asked if the Army was developing an alternative to the GCV, Chiarelli replied "We're totally committed to GCV."<ref name="Defense news interview w. Chiarreli">{{Cite web |last=Brannen |first=Kate |date=25 October 2010 |title=Gen. Peter Chiarelli |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4965011&c=FEA&s=INT |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130122002756/http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4965011&c=FEA&s=INT |archive-date=22 January 2013 |access-date=24 October 2010 |work=Army Times }}</ref> The [[National Commission on Fiscal Responsibility and Reform]] suggested deferring development of the GCV until after 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 October 2010 |title=$200 BILLION IN ILLUSTRATIVE SAVINGS |url=http://www.fiscalcommission.gov/sites/fiscalcommission.gov/files/documents/Illustrative_List_11.10.2010.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101119153741/http://www.fiscalcommission.gov/sites/fiscalcommission.gov/files/documents/Illustrative_List_11.10.2010.pdf |archive-date=19 November 2010 |access-date=11 November 2010 |df=dmy-all}}</ref>

;Projections
[[File:GCV Infantry Fighting Vehicle schedule (January 2010).png|thumb|right|300px|The IFV schedule as of January 2010]]
The Technology Development Phase was to begin with the award of up to three vehicle contracts in late FY2010.<ref name="GCV PROGRAM PLAN"/> The Army planned to spend $7.6 billion during this phase.<ref name="Lucrative contracts">{{cite web|title=Contractors vie for lucrative vehicle work|url=https://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/168352-contractors-vie-for-lucrative-vehicle-work/|access-date=6 August 2010|author=Roxana Tiron|date=6 August 2010|archive-date=22 June 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622032125/http://thehill.com/business-a-lobbying/112959-top-contractors-vie-for-lucrative-vehicle-work|url-status=live}}</ref>

The Engineering and Manufacturing Development Phase was to begin with two prototype development contracts awarded in the beginning of FY2013. The first prototypes would be manufactured mid-FY2015.<ref name="GCV PROGRAM PLAN" />

The [[Low rate initial production|Low Rate Initial Production]] Phase was to begin with a low-rate production contract awarded in mid FY2016. Less than two years after the contract award LRIP would begin. After more testing a [[battalion]]-sized team would be attained in FY2018 followed by a [[brigade]]-sized arsenal in FY2019.<ref name="GCV PROGRAM PLAN" />

The Army would then decide whether to go into full-rate production. The Army planned on procuring 1,450 IFVs at a total program cost of $40 billion.<ref name="GCV PROGRAM PLAN" /><ref name="1,450">{{cite web|title=Panel rejects bid to divert funds for Bradley upgrades|url=http://www.govexec.com/dailyfed/0810/080410cdam2.htm|work=Government Executive|publisher=National Journal Group|access-date=4 August 2010|author=Megan Scully|date=4 August 2010|archive-date=26 August 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100826050627/http://www.govexec.com/dailyfed/0810/080410cdam2.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref>
