=== Revised program ===
An industry day was held in October in Dearborn, Michigan.<ref name="Tiered">{{cite web|title=U.S. Army to Set Out Tiered Requirements for GCV|url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4826208&c=LAN&s=TOP|work=Defense News|access-date=26 October 2010|last=Brannen |first=Kate|date=5 October 2010}}{{dead link|date=August 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The Army reduced its requested FY 2011 budget to $462 million.<ref name="$462 million"/> Advanced Defense Vehicle Systems, General Dynamics Land Systems, and BAE Systems announced their intention of re-competing soon after the cancellation.<ref name="Crains resubmit">{{cite web|title=Contractors to resubmit bids for revamped military vehicle program|url=http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20100926/SUB01/309269952/contractors-to-resubmit-bids-for-revamped-military-vehicle-program|publisher=Crain Communications Inc.|access-date=27 September 2010|author=Chad Halcom|date=26 September 2010|archive-date=6 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170906134223/http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20100926/SUB01/309269952/contractors-to-resubmit-bids-for-revamped-military-vehicle-program|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Military vehicle maker drops protest, will try again for government contracts|url=http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20100827/FREE/100829898|publisher=Crain Communications Inc.|access-date=30 August 2010|author=Chad Halcom|date=27 August 2010|archive-date=30 August 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100830063534/http://www.crainsdetroit.com/article/20100827/FREE/100829898|url-status=live}}</ref>

The revised RfP was issued in November. ADVS announced that it would not submit a proposal due to the program's extended timeline.<ref>{{cite web|title=4th GCV team withdraws from competition|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2011/08/defense-gcv-gets-go-ahead-081811/|work= Army Times|access-date=19 January 2011|last=Brannen |first=Kate|date=18 January 2011}}</ref>

Up to three [[cost-plus contract]]s were to be awarded nine months after the RfP was released.<ref name="delay"/><ref name="Ground Combat Vehicle Technology Development Phase Solicitation 2">{{cite web|title=10--Ground Combat Vehicle Technology Development Phase Solicitation|url=https://www.fbo.gov/index?s=opportunity&mode=form&tab=core&id=3ca68abe44eae4d617512b7057977a18&_cview=0|access-date=16 October 2010|date=8 October 2010|archive-date=1 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120601161454/https://www.fbo.gov/index?s=opportunity&mode=form&tab=core&id=3ca68abe44eae4d617512b7057977a18&_cview=0|url-status=live}}</ref> The Army delivered an analysis of alternatives to Congress in April 2011. The notional GCV fared well compared to comparable vehicles including the Stryker and foreign counterparts such as the Israeli [[Namer]] and German [[Puma (IFV)|Puma]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bertuca |first1=Tony |title=Stryker not lethal enough, Bradley not big enough JOURNAL ARTICLE Stryker not lethal enough, Bradley not big enough: Lawmakers, Auditors Get A Chance to Examine Army's Analysis On GCV |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/24833515 |access-date=10 January 2023 |work=Inside the Army |issue=15 |publisher=Inside Washington Publishers |date=18 April 2011 |volume=23 |jstor=24833515 |archive-date=10 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230110060818/https://www.jstor.org/stable/24833515 |url-status=live }}</ref> An acquisition decision memorandum in August 2011 allowed the program to award technology development contracts. It also initiated two reviews of alternatives including a revised analysis of alternatives and an analysis of non-developmental vehicles.<ref>{{cite web|title=GCV moves ahead, but more studies ordered|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2011/08/defense-gcv-gets-go-ahead-081811/ |work=Army Times|access-date=11 September 2011|last=Brannen |first=Kate|date=18 August 2011}}</ref> In August, the Army awarded technology development contracts to BAE and GDLS. BAE was awarded $450 million while GDLS was awarded $440 million.<ref>{{cite web|title=BAE, GD awarded Ground Combat Vehicle contracts|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2011/08/defense-army-gcv-contract-winners-announced-081811/ |work=Army Times|access-date=11 September 2011|last=Brannen |first=Kate|date=18 August 2011}}</ref> SAIC protest the award later that month,<ref>{{cite web|title=SAIC-Led Team Protests U.S. Army Combat Vehicle Contracts|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-26/saic-boeing-team-said-to-protest-army-combat-vehicle-contracts.html|publisher=Bloomberg L.P|access-date=11 September 2011|author=Roxana Tiron and Brendan McGarry|date=26 August 2011|archive-date=6 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121106160100/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-26/saic-boeing-team-said-to-protest-army-combat-vehicle-contracts.html|url-status=live}}</ref> saying it believed the evaluations process was flawed and the evaluation took factors into consideration that were not stated in the request for proposal.<ref>{{cite web|title=U.S. Ground Combat Vehicle Work Put On Hold|url=http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story_channel.jsp?channel=defense&id=news/asd/2011/08/30/07.xml&headline=U.S.%20Ground%20Combat%20Vehicle%20Work%20Put%20On%20Hold|publisher=Bloomberg L.P|access-date=11 September 2011|author=Paul McLeary|date=29 August 2011}}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The Army suspended work on the GCV until December, when the [[Government Accountability Office]] denied SAIC's protest.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tony |first1=Bertuca |title=Puma still in play for AOA: Army Lifts Stop-Work Order On GCV After GAO Denies SAIC Bid Protest |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/24834209 |access-date=11 January 2023 |work=Inside the Army |issue=49 |publisher=Inside Washington Publishers |date=12 December 2011 |volume=23 |jstor=24834209 |archive-date=11 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230111020232/https://www.jstor.org/stable/24834209 |url-status=live }}</ref>

;Projections
The Army requested $884 million to fund the GCV in FY 2012.<ref name="Kate FY 2012">{{cite web|title=Army seeks 30 percent less for overseas ops|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2011/02/defense-army-overseas-ops-budget-021411/ |work=Army Times|access-date=15 February 2011|last=Brannen |first=Kate|date=15 February 2011}}</ref> The technology development phase was to be a 24 months long, 3 months shorter than the previous plan.<ref name="Revised. Kate Brannen">{{cite web|title=U.S. Army To Host GCV Industry Day Oct. 1|url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4787079&c=LAN&s=TOP|work=Defense News|access-date=22 September 2010|last=Brannen |first=Kate|date=22 September 2010}}{{dead link|date=August 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The Engineering and Manufacturing Development phase was to be 48 months long.<ref name="revised program Industry day">{{cite web|title=GCV Industry Day|url=http://contracting.tacom.army.mil/majorsys/gcv/GCV%20Industry%20Day%20Brief%20Oct%2010%20Charts.pdf|access-date=13 November 2010|date=1 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722184210/http://contracting.tacom.army.mil/majorsys/gcv/GCV%20Industry%20Day%20Brief%20Oct%2010%20Charts.pdf|archive-date=22 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> The Army planned on acquiring 1,874 GCVs to replace Bradleys in 16 active and 8 National Guard [[Brigade Combat Team#Armored Brigade Combat Team|Heavy Brigade Combat Teams]].<ref name="BAE">{{cite news |title=BAE Offers 70-ton GCV |url=http://www.armytimes.com/article/20120324/NEWS/203240316/Heavyweight-contender-BAE-offers-70-ton-GCV |work=Army Times |publisher=Gannett |date=27 March 2012}}</ref>

;Milestone A
[[File:Namer in US.jpg|thumb|A [[Namer APC]] during non-developmental vehicle assessment]]
[[File:CV9035 assessment (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|A [[Combat Vehicle 90|CV-9035]] demonstrator vehicle for the non-developmental vehicle assessment]]

Testing of commercially available combat vehicles began in May 2012 at [[Fort Bliss]] and [[White Sands Missile Range]] to prepare the Army for Milestone B. The non-developmental vehicle analysis assessed five vehicles, the [[M2A3 Bradley]], [[Namer]], [[Combat Vehicle 90|CV-9035]], a double v-hulled M1126 infantry carrier vehicle and a turretless Bradley. The tests, completed that month, were carried out to determine what vehicle variants and configurations fulfill the Army's needs.<ref name="NDV Assessments">{{cite news |title=Army assesses current vehicles as part of Ground Combat Vehicle development process |author=Ashley Piper |url=https://www.army.mil/article/80185/The_Desert_Heats_Up_as_GCV_Kicks_Off_Non_Developmental_Vehicle__NDV__Assessments/ |newspaper=Army News |date=21 May 2012 |access-date=8 June 2012 |archive-date=5 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150605102404/http://www.army.mil/article/80185/The_Desert_Heats_Up_as_GCV_Kicks_Off_Non_Developmental_Vehicle__NDV__Assessments/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The Army found that although the vehicles assessed met some GCV requirements, no currently fielded vehicle met enough without needing significant redesign.<ref name="response">{{cite news |title=Army, industry slam CBO's scathing GCV report |url=https://www.military.com/dodbuzz/2013/04/04/army-industry-slam-cbos-scathing-gcv-report |access-date=10 January 2023 |work=Military.com |date=4 April 2013 |archive-date=10 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230110011536/https://www.military.com/dodbuzz/2013/04/04/army-industry-slam-cbos-scathing-gcv-report |url-status=live }}</ref>

;Competitors
There were three competing contractors for the Ground Combat Vehicle contract.

*[[BAE Systems]], [[Northrop Grumman]], [[QinetiQ]] North America,  [[Saft Groupe S.A.|Saft Group]], and [[iRobot]] were working jointly on development
*[[General Dynamics Land Systems]] led a team that included [[Lockheed Martin]] and [[Raytheon]]
*[[Science Applications International Corporation|SAIC]] led a team that include [[Boeing]], [[Krauss-Maffei Wegmann]] and [[Rheinmetall Defence]] (not awarded EMD contract)

;Milestone C
A Milestone C decision could have been made in 2019.<ref name="weight">{{cite web|last=Cox|first=Matt|title=Army: GCV Needs to Be Big and Tracked|url=http://defensetech.org/2013/02/21/army-gcv-needs-to-be-big-and-tracked/|publisher=DefenseTech|access-date=February 26, 2013|date=February 21, 2013|archive-date=25 January 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210125110203/http://www.defensetech.org/2013/02/21/army-gcv-needs-to-be-big-and-tracked/|url-status=usurped}}</ref>

===Budget concerns and proposed cuts===
In December 2012, it was reported that the Army may need to cut $150 million from the GCV program in 2014, with deeper cuts between $600–700 million between 2014 and 2018. This put the program, one of the Army's highest priorities, at serious risk. With the drawdown of the [[War in Afghanistan (2001–present)|War in Afghanistan]] and budgetary concerns, the expensive development of a new combat vehicle was not seen as feasible. BAE Systems and [[General Dynamics]] were each awarded engineering and manufacturing development (EMD) phase contracts in August 2011. The EMD phase was to last 48 months for both contractors. Senate appropriators were also concerned that the GCV would compete with the Army's other combat modernization priorities. Though the GCV would make up only 10 percent of the Army combat vehicle fleet, the Army had programmed 80 percent of its combat vehicle modernization budget for the GCV over the next five years.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bertuca |first1=Tony |title=Massive GCV Cuts On The Table As Army 'Reviews' Program |url=http://insidedefense.com/201212052418071/Inside-Defense-General/Public-Articles/massive-gcv-cuts-on-the-table-as-army-reviews-program/menu-id-926.html |access-date=10 January 2023 |work=Inside the Army |issue=49 |publisher=Inside Washington Publishers |date=10 December 2012 |volume=24 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130127175742/http://insidedefense.com/201212052418071/Inside-Defense-General/Public-Articles/massive-gcv-cuts-on-the-table-as-army-reviews-program/menu-id-926.html#selection-361.1-361.56 |archive-date=27 January 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

===Revision===
The Army revised the GCV acquisition strategy in January 2013 to reduce risk and maintain affordability of the program. The revision extended the technology development phase by six months to give industry more time to refine vehicle designs. Milestone B would occur in 2014, with the selection of a single vendor for the engineering and manufacturing development (EMD) phase of the program. Budgetary pressures caused the Army to reduce the number of vendors to be selected for EMD from two to one.<ref name="3rd revision">{{Cite news |date=18 January 2013 |title=Army Ground Combat Vehicle Acquisition Strategy Revised |work=Army Public Affairs |url=https://www.army.mil/article/94605/ |access-date=22 January 2013 |archive-date=24 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130224212941/http://www.army.mil/article/94605/ |url-status=live }}</ref> The Army expected this change would save the DoD $2.5 billion.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bertuca |first1=Tony |title=Move to single EMD vendor would save $2.5 billion: Pentagon Affirms Major GCV Program Changes For Billions In Savings |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/24836807 |access-date=10 January 2023 |work=Inside the Army |issue=3 |date=21 January 2013 |volume=25 |jstor=24836807 |archive-date=10 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230110221819/https://www.jstor.org/stable/24836807 |url-status=live }}</ref>

===CBO report===
In April 2013, the [[Congressional Budget Office]] (CBO) issued a report on the progress of the GCV program. The report questioned the program, estimated to cost $28 billion from 2014 to 2030, with the possibility of alternate vehicle options. While none met overall Army goals desired in the GCV, they offered advantages in being less costly and delayed. Planned GCV prototypes were heavy, weighing up to 84 tons, to be better protected and seat a nine-man squad. Officials said that a vehicle of that size would not be well suited to operations faced in Iraq or Afghanistan. Alternate vehicles would be cheaper and more maneuverable in urban settings. The CBO report analyzed four alternative options:<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hoffman |first1=Michael |title=Report: GCV is worst choice to replace Bradley |url=http://www.dodbuzz.com/2013/04/03/report-gcv-is-worst-choice-to-replace-bradley/ |access-date=10 January 2023 |work=DoD Buzz |publisher=Military Advantage |date=3 April 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171023162044/https://www.dodbuzz.com/2013/04/03/report-gcv-is-worst-choice-to-replace-bradley/ |archive-date=23 October 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref><ref>{{cite report |date=April 2013 |title=The Army's Ground Combat Vehicle Program and Alternatives |url=https://www.cbo.gov/sites/default/files/113th-congress-2013-2014/reports/44044-GCV-1column.pdf |publisher=Congressional Budget Office |access-date=10 January 2023 |archive-date=28 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220828055104/https://www.cbo.gov/sites/default/files/113th-congress-2013-2014/reports/44044-GCV-1column.pdf |url-status=live }}</ref>
* Purchase the Namer APC – Seats 9 soldiers with combat survival rates expected slightly higher than the GCV, and costs $9 billion less. The Namer has less ability to destroy other enemy vehicles and is less mobile. Production would be conducted in part domestically, but fielding would require collaboration with foreign companies and governments.
* Upgrade the Bradley IFV – An upgraded Bradley would be more lethal than the GCV against enemy forces and would probably survive combat at about the same rates as would the GCV, saving $19.8 billion. Upgrading the Bradley would make it "significantly more capable" than the GCV. The Bradley still only carries a 7-man squad and has less mobility.
* Purchase the [[Puma (IFV)|Puma]] – More lethal than the GCV, combat survival and protection at better rates, and just as mobile. Purchasing the Puma would save $14.8 billion and was considered the most capable of the vehicles. Puma IFVs only carry six infantrymen, which would require five vehicles to replace every four Bradleys. Development and production would require collaboration with foreign companies and governments.
* Cancel the Ground Combat Vehicle – If the Army reconditioned its current Bradley instead of replacing them, the current capability of the IFV fleet could be maintained through 2030. The Army could continue to investigate ways to improve the current Bradleys, but it would not field any new or improved vehicles. The $24 billion saved in funding could be used on other programs.

General Dynamics and BAE Systems, who received contracts in the Ground Combat Vehicle program, criticized the CBO report, saying they used the wrong vehicle in its analysis. Officials from both companies said they used the wrong notional model of the GCV that did not account for the change in requirements made by the Army or the advancements made in the technology development phase of the program. They also criticized the comparisons of the other vehicles. The report factored cost, survivability, mobility, and lethality, ranking the GCV's capabilities as lower than all others. The Army questioned the suitability of existing design. An Army test of currently fielded vehicles in 2012 revealed that some met critical GCV requirements, but none met enough without needing significant redesign. They also note that lethality was judged with a 25&nbsp;mm cannon for analysis, before the Army planned to mount a 30&nbsp;mm cannon. The CBO report did give credit to cost, assuming the Army's goal of $13 million per vehicle. However, Pentagon cost assessments estimated the price at $16–$17 million per vehicle.<ref name="response"/>

===Funding cut and prioritization===
In July 2013, Army Chief of Staff General [[Ray Odierno]] warned that the GCV program might be delayed or possibly even cancelled because of the sequestration budget cuts. In August 2013, Defense Secretary [[Chuck Hagel]] outlined two basic results if the effects of sequestration continued: modernization programs like the GCV would be cut to maintain troop levels, or high-end capability efforts like the GCV would be preserved to continue modernization and keep equipment technologically advanced with troop levels being cut. Odierno was committed to balancing soldiers, readiness, and modernization, and was intent on the need for the Ground Combat Vehicle.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Sisk |first1=Richard |title=Odierno: GCV in Danger of Cancelation |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2013/07/30/gcv-in-danger-of-cancelation.html?ESRC=todayinmil.sm |access-date=11 January 2023 |work=Military.com |publisher=Military Advantage |date=30 July 2013 |archive-date=11 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230111014148/https://www.military.com/daily-news/2013/07/30/gcv-in-danger-of-cancelation.html?ESRC=todayinmil.sm |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Ground Combat Vehicle may be delayed – or canceled |url=http://www.armytimes.com/article/20130805/NEWS04/308050022/Ground-Combat-Vehicle-may-delayed-canceled |work=Army Times |publisher=Gannett |date=5 August 2013}}</ref>

Some reports{{Clarify|date=November 2014}} suggested that the [[Armored Multi-Purpose Vehicle]] (AMPV) program to replace the M113 family of vehicles was being favored over the GCV program. While procurement of the AMPV fleet would cost over $5 billion, the [[Government Accountability Office]] estimated the GCV fleet would cost $37 billion. A September 2013 [[Congressional Research Service]] report suggested that given budgetary constraints, the GCV program may be unrealistic, and that one potential discussion could focus on a decision by the Army to replace the GCV with the AMPV as their number one ground combat vehicle acquisition priority.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McLeary |first1=Paul |title=US Army Looks To Delay, Increase Cost of AMPV Program |url=http://www.defensenews.com/article/20131002/DEFREG02/310020011/US-Army-Looks-Delay-Increase-Cost-AMPV-Program |access-date=11 January 2023 |work=Defense News |publisher=Gannett Government Media Corporation |date=2 October 2013 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20131006111913/http://www.defensenews.com/article/20131002/DEFREG02/310020011/US-Army-Looks-Delay-Increase-Cost-AMPV-Program |archive-date=6 October 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> An October 2013 Congressional Budget Office report found that $16 billion could be saved over the next 13 years if the GCV were canceled in favor of Bradley upgrades.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bertuca |first1=Tony |title=Pros, cons and billions in savings: CBO Lays Out Potential Plan To Cancel Army's Ground Combat Vehicle |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/24836079 |access-date=10 January 2023 |work=Inside the Army |issue=46 |publisher=Inside Washington Publishers |date=18 November 2013 |volume=25 |jstor=24836079 |archive-date=10 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230110065705/https://www.jstor.org/stable/24836079 |url-status=live }}</ref>

By mid-November 2013, both BAE and General Dynamics designs had passed Preliminary Design Reviews (PDR), but neither company had commenced building prototypes. The Army was increasingly willing to slow down the GCV program or push it back from EMD to research and development. While the Army had said previously that the GCV was their highest priority acquisition program, they had since shifted their main modernization priority to an integrated electronic command network.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Freedberg Jr. |first1=Sydney J. |title=Big Army For Big Wars? Yes! GCV? Probably Not. |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2013/11/army-regime-change-maybe-gcv-probably-not/ |access-date=11 January 2023 |work=Breaking Defense |publisher=Breaking Media |date=13 November 2013 |archive-date=11 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230111015648/https://breakingdefense.com/2013/11/army-regime-change-maybe-gcv-probably-not/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

In January 2014, a spending bill passed by the House appropriated $100 million for the GCV program, even though the Army had requested $592 million for the program for FY2014. The Army planned to spend 80 percent of its ground vehicle modernization budget on the GCV over the next five years, with costs ranging from $29–34 billion. Several options were being considered to make the program more affordable, including reducing the squad size from nine men and using new emerging and undeveloped technologies to reduce the weight of the vehicle to 30 tons for operations in urban environments.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Bacon |first=Lance M. |date=15 January 2014 |title=Ground Combat Vehicle Budget Slashed, Cancellation More Likely |url=http://www.militarytimes.com/article/20140115/NEWS05/301150035/Ground-combat-vehicle-budget-slashed-cancellation-more-likely |access-date=15 January 2014 |website=Military Times |archive-date=16 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140116014114/http://www.militarytimes.com/article/20140115/NEWS05/301150035/Ground-combat-vehicle-budget-slashed-cancellation-more-likely |url-status=dead }}</ref> The two contractors would run out of money for development of their prototype vehicles by June 2014 unless the Army funded the rest of the technology development phase. The Pentagon and Army tried to find ways to continue the program, without actually starting vehicle production, through new technologies like advanced fire control systems and hybrid engines. Although the Army wanted 1,894 Ground Combat Vehicles with a target price of $9–10.5 million per unit, the Pentagon's Office of Cost Assessment and Program Evaluation estimated a [[unit cost]] of up to $17 million.<ref>[https://archive.today/20140119182437/http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140118/DEFSECT02/301180024/US-Army-s-GCV-Program-Downgraded-Study-Project US Army's GCV Program Downgraded To Study Project] – Defensenews.com, 18 January 2014</ref> The 83 percent cut in funding essentially scaled back the GCV program to a research effort. The program had declined in support over the past months with the Army determining that the desired vehicle was no longer feasible in the near term due to budget reductions, suspicion from the contractors that the program would not move past technology development, and Congress's belief it would not succeed.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cox |first1=Matthew |title=GCV's Loss Will Reset Army Buying Priorities |url=http://www.military.com/daily-news/2014/01/22/gcvs-loss-will-reset-army-buying-priorities.html?ESRC=todayinmil.sm |access-date=13 May 2024 |work=Military.com |date=22 January 2014 |language=en}}</ref>

In January 2014, Odierno confirmed that the GCV program was being put on hold due to budget difficulties. Odierno said that the Army needed a new IFV but that they could not afford one at the time. Odierno said that he was pleased with the requirements for the vehicle and that progress and development with the contractors was good.<ref name="defensenews23jan14">[http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20140124134526/http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140123/DEFREG02/301230041/US%2DArmy%2DChief%2DConfirms%2DGround%2DCombat%2DVehicle%2DDead%2DNow%2D US Army Chief Confirms: Ground Combat Vehicle Is Dead (For Now)] – Defensenews.com, 23 January 2014</ref> Science and technology investments were to be made to address the size and weight of armored ground vehicles to make it easier and cheaper to transport greater numbers of them across the world.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McLeary |first1=Paul |title=Army leaders preview lighter, faster service |url=http://www.militarytimes.com/article/20140128/NEWS/301280010/Army-leaders-preview-lighter-faster-service|access-date=13 May 2024 |work=Military Times |publisher=Gannett |date=28 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140128161012/http://www.militarytimes.com/article/20140128/NEWS/301280010/Army-leaders-preview-lighter-faster-service|archive-date=28 January 2014 }}</ref> On the recommendation of the Army, the DoD formally canceled the GCV program in February 2014.{{sfn|Feickert|2014|p=9}}

==Weight issues==
In November 2012, estimates of the GCV's weight, depending on armor packages, put the General Dynamics entry vehicle at 64–70 tons, and the BAE Systems entry vehicle at 70–84 tons. This made the planned infantry fighting vehicle designs heavier than the [[M1 Abrams]] tank. The reason was the vehicle had to have enough armor to protect a squad of nine troops from all battlefield threats (from [[rocket-propelled grenade]]s to [[Improvised explosive device|IED]]s) as good as or better than other vehicles can protect against specific threats individually. This worked against the vehicle; as weight increases, cost goes up and maneuverability goes down. The contractors worked to bring the weight down.<ref>{{Citation |title=Bradley Offspring, GCV, May Top 84 Tons, Heavier Than M1 Tank |date=November 8, 2012 |url=http://defense.aol.com/2012/11/08/bradley-offspring-gcv-may-top-84-tons-hheavier-than-m1-tank/ |work=Defense |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121112072248/http://defense.aol.com/2012/11/08/bradley-offspring-gcv-may-top-84-tons-hheavier-than-m1-tank |publisher=AOL |access-date=2012-11-13 |archive-date=2012-11-12 |url-status=dead}}.</ref> The Army maintained that heavy armor was needed to protect the squad from acceleration forces that come with an underside blast, and that thicker underbelly plates and [[V-hull|V-shaped hulls]] do not give enough protection. More armor would come from the vehicle being larger for more internal space for the soldiers, and to allow for features such as floating floors for blast deflection and extra headroom. The Army also said heavy weight would not affect deployability because the Bradley it was planned to replace already requires [[Airlift#Strategic airlift|strategic airlift]] [[Military transport aircraft|transport aircraft]].<ref name="weight"/>

Both contractors claimed their designs were below the 70–84 tons expectation of what the GCV will weigh. BAE's vehicle weighed 60–70 tons, based on modular armor package, and a 20 percent margin for weight increase the Army had planned for future upgrades would bring it up to 84 tons. General Dynamic's vehicle with a diesel engine weighed 62 tons in its most heavily armored configuration, which increased to 76 tons with the 20 percent future upgrade margin. Removing protection for easier air transportation would have reduced it to 56 tons. The Army's consideration to slow down the GCV development program gave time to the companies to refine their designs and reduce weight. One way would have been to reduce squad size. A nine-man squad has been identified as best for being able to fight with the possibility of taking casualties with single-vehicle transportability. With a three-man crew, the GCV had to carry 12 men. A greater number of lighter IFVs that carry fewer soldiers would have similar carrying capacity and combined costs and weight to planned GCV numbers. Another way would be an advance in armor designs. Lighter and stronger armor materials had not made radical progressions in recent history, and domestic active protection intercept systems were not yet mature. Foreign systems like the Israeli [[Trophy (countermeasure)|Trophy]] had seen combat but cannot yet intercept tank shells. The GCV program originally included an APS, but was then delayed as a feature for later upgrades. The last effort to replace the Bradley had been FCS from 2003 to 2009, which developed a vehicle that relied on sensors to avoid danger and an APS in place of heavy armor. It was too ambitious for the time and the vehicle's weight had grown from 19 tons to 30 tons by the time it was cancelled.<ref>{{Citation |title=BAE, GD: We Can Cut Weight From Army's GCV |date=27 November 2013 |url=http://breakingdefense.com/2013/11/bae-general-dynamics-we-can-get-weight-down-on-army-gcv/ |work=Breaking defense |access-date=14 July 2022 |archive-date=3 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131203040225/http://breakingdefense.com/2013/11/bae-general-dynamics-we-can-get-weight-down-on-army-gcv/ |url-status=live }}.</ref>

==Termination==
In February 2014, Defense Secretary [[Chuck Hagel]] canceled the GCV, accepting the Army's request to do so.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bertuca |first1=Tony |last2=Judson |first2=Jen |title=Hagel Cuts Army's Size, Kills GCV, Backs Service Aviation Restructure Plans |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/insipent.30.9.18 |access-date=10 January 2023 |work=Inside the Pentagon |issue=9 |publisher=Inside Washington Publishers |date=27 February 2014 |volume=30 |archive-date=10 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230110063305/https://www.jstor.org/stable/insipent.30.9.18 |url-status=live }}</ref> Army acquisition executive [[Heidi Shyu]] said that criticism of the program was "unfortunate" and cancelling it had nothing to do with vehicle performance. Shyu said the program had been doing "remarkably well" and wasn't having technical issues, and that the contracts were being executed well. The decision to cancel development was based entirely on budget calculations, with no possible way to come up with funds no matter how many other areas were reduced Money will be redistributed to engineering change proposals (ECP) on existing platforms until budget difficulties pass to allow investment in next-generation capabilities in about seven years.<ref>[https://archive.today/20140301164158/http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140225/DEFREG02/302250025/US-Army-Official-Defends-GCV-Against-Attacks- US Army Official Defends GCV Against 'Attacks'] - Defensenews.com, 25 February 2014</ref>

The decision had to be made to either exclusively fund the GCV or ECPs, so upgrades were chosen for the Bradley, Abrams, Stryker, and [[M109 Paladin]]. Vehicles like the Bradley and Abrams have been upgraded since the 1980s with new armor, sensors, and other gear that have maxed out the platforms for further horsepower and electrical advances, so the requirement for an entirely new ground combat vehicle built from the outset from lessons learned in combat from the previous decade remains.<ref>[http://breakingdefense.com/2014/03/shyu-sings-the-army-electric-services-2015-budget-sacrifices-weapons-for-electronics/ Shyu Sings The Army Electric: 2015 Budget Sacrifices Weapons For Electronics] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140309184610/http://breakingdefense.com/2014/03/shyu-sings-the-army-electric-services-2015-budget-sacrifices-weapons-for-electronics/ |date=9 March 2014 }} - Breakingdefense.com, 3 March 2014</ref> The Army's own budget proposal unveiled in March discontinued the program, and instead funds were shifted to the AMPV program as the main vehicle priority and to improving the Bradley IFV in the interim until more resources become available.<ref>[http://www.dodbuzz.com/2014/03/04/army-2015-budget-kills-gcv-cuts-readiness/ Army 2015 Budget Kills GCV, Cuts Readiness] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140306015030/http://www.dodbuzz.com/2014/03/04/army-2015-budget-kills-gcv-cuts-readiness/ |date=6 March 2014 }} - DoDBuzz.com, 4 March 2014</ref><ref>[https://www.army.mil/article/121217/FY15_Army_budget__request_includes_small_pay_raise__490K_end_strength/ FY15 Army budget, request includes small pay raise, 490K end strength]  - Army.mil, 4 March 2014</ref> Incremental improvements will be made to current vehicle fleets to improve protection and networking abilities. $131 million will be directed into science and technology to look at the feasibility of future combat vehicle technologies, and Secretary Hagel has directed the Army, as well as the Marine Corps, to deliver "realistic" visions for vehicle modernization by the end of FY 2014.<ref>[https://archive.today/20140310100134/http://www.nationaldefensemagazine.org/blog/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=1435 Army Budget Makes Force Structure, Modernization Cuts Official] - Nationaldefensemagazine.org, 4 March 2014</ref>

The cancellation of the GCV is the second time in 15 years an Army program to replace the Bradley has failed. FCS ran from 1999 to 2009, with the Manned Ground Vehicles portion for replacing several armored vehicle classes costing "hundreds of millions" of dollars out of $20 billion total. From 2010 to 2014, the Army spent over $1 billion on the GCV. Although there was criticism that vehicle weight could not be kept at a reasonable level while meeting its size and power requirements, the Army maintains the official reason for the cancellation was budgetary pressures. BAE Systems and General Dynamics will each receive $50 million in FY 2015 to continue technology development. The next follow-up IFV development program is currently named the Future Fighting Vehicle (FFV).<ref name="defensenews6april14" />

== Legacy == 
{{main|XM30 Mechanized Infantry Combat Vehicle}}
At the time of the GCV's cancelation, it was thought that the Army might direct some funds for technology development so that it could start another program within "three to four years."<ref name="defensenews23jan14"/> In August 2014 GDLS and BAE Systems Land and Armaments were awarded $7.9 million each to develop technologies from the GCV program for the Future Fighting Vehicle (FFV) program.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roosevelt |first1=Ann |date=19 August 2014 |title=General Dynamics, BAE Systems Win Study Contracts For Future Fighting Vehicle |url=https://www.defensedaily.com/general-dynamics-bae-systems-win-study-contracts-for-future-fighting-vehicle/army/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230702205610/https://www.defensedaily.com/general-dynamics-bae-systems-win-study-contracts-for-future-fighting-vehicle/army/ |archive-date=2 July 2023 |access-date=22 January 2022 |website=Defense Daily}}</ref> Citing budget constraints, in August 2015, the Army delayed the FFV's acquisition decision from FY2021 to FY2029. The Army said it was choosing to instead work on short-term capability gaps.<ref name="FFV Delay">{{cite news |last1=Mitchell |first1=Ellen |date=31 August 2015 |title=Army Delays Future Fighting Vehicle To FY-29 |url=https://insidedefense.com/daily-news/army-delays-future-fighting-vehicle-fy-29 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220122095935/https://insidedefense.com/daily-news/army-delays-future-fighting-vehicle-fy-29 |archive-date=22 January 2022 |access-date=22 January 2022 |work=Inside Defense}}</ref> In June 2018, the Army established what would become the [[Optionally Manned Fighting Vehicle]] (OMFV) program to replace the M2 Bradley.<ref name="NGCV portfolio">{{cite news |last1=Tressel |first1=Ashley |date=12 October 2018 |title=MPF, AMPV now part of NGCV family of vehicles |url=https://insidedefense.com/daily-news/mpf-ampv-now-part-ngcv-family-vehicles. |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231225002327/https://insidedefense.com/daily-news/mpf-ampv-now-part-ngcv-family-vehicles#:~:text=The%20Next%20Generation%20Combat%20Vehicle,%2C%20Armored%20Multi%2DPurpose%20Vehicle. |archive-date=25 December 2023 |access-date=21 January 2022 |work=Inside Defense}}</ref> In June 2023, the Army downselected American [[Rheinmetall]] and GDLS to go forward in the competition for the OMFV contract, now designated the XM30 Mechanized Infantry Combat Vehicle.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Roque |first1=Ashley |date=26 June 2023 |title=OMFV finalists: Rheinmetall, GDLS again square off for Bradley replacement competition |url=https://breakingdefense.com/2023/06/omfv-race-narrows-rheinmetall-gdls-again-square-off-for-bradley-replacement-competition/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231221215421/https://breakingdefense.com/2023/06/omfv-race-narrows-rheinmetall-gdls-again-square-off-for-bradley-replacement-competition/ |archive-date=21 December 2023 |access-date=26 June 2023 |website=Breaking Defense}}</ref>

==Design==
Following the cancelation of the Future Combat Systems family the Army assessed that a new [[infantry fighting vehicle]] (IFV) would be its first priority with the GCV program. The Army determined that it would reset the [[M1 Abrams]] [[main battle tank]], the [[M2 Bradley]] IFV and the [[M109 Paladin]] [[self-propelled howitzer]] in the meantime while the GCV was undergoing development.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Censer |first1=Marjorie |title=First Configuration to Be Infantry Fighting Vehicle: Chiarelli: Ground Combat Vehicle Will Be 'Upgradeable,' Versatile |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/24831175 |access-date=10 January 2023 |work=Inside the Army |publisher=Inside Washington Publishers |date=14 September 2009 |jstor=24831175 |archive-date=10 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230110231426/https://www.jstor.org/stable/24831175 |url-status=live }}</ref> The GCV could later serve as the common [[chassis]] for a family of vehicles to replace legacy armored vehicles.<ref name="Lance & Shield">{{Cite web |title=US Army Defines Ground Combat Vehicles (GCV) Priorities |url=http://defense-update.com/newscast/0909/news/220909_ground_combat_vehicle.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316211643/http://defense-update.com/newscast/0909/news/220909_ground_combat_vehicle.html |archive-date=16 March 2010 |access-date=29 March 2010 |website=Defense Update |publisher=Lance & Shield}}</ref>

The Army emphasized affordability, rapid deployment, and low-risk technology for the GCV. The Army required that all aspects of the GCV be at [[technology readiness level]] 6.<ref name="Greg">{{cite web|title=Army Wants Tough GCV Battle|url=http://www.dodbuzz.com/2010/03/05/army-wants-tough-gcv-competition/|publisher=Military Advantage|access-date=11 August 2010|author=Greg Grant|date=March 5, 2010|archive-date=24 April 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100424200807/http://www.dodbuzz.com/2010/03/05/army-wants-tough-gcv-competition/|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="contracting.tacom.army.mil">{{cite web|url=http://contracting.tacom.army.mil/majorsys/gcv/attach/Attch%200001_GCV%20IFV%20Statement%20of%20Work_RFP%20Amendments.pdf|title=Ground Combat Vehicle Infantry Fighting Vehicle Statement of Work|work=United States Army|date=March 15, 2009|access-date=April 7, 2010}}{{dead link|date=April 2025|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> The shortfalls of rapid deployment would be mitigated through an incremental addition of components as technology matures.<ref name=Optimizing>{{cite web |url=http://www.bctmod.army.mil/GCV_focus/GCV%20Narrative.pdf |title=The Ground Combat Vehicle Strategy: Optimizing for the Future |publisher=U.S. Army |access-date=December 14, 2009 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110430044607/http://www.bctmod.army.mil/GCV_focus/GCV%20Narrative.pdf |archive-date=April 30, 2011 }}</ref> The Army provided details from the [[Future Combat Systems]] (FCS) [[FCS Manned Ground Vehicles|Manned Ground Vehicles]] (MGV) effort to utilize on the GCV.<ref name="contracting.tacom.army.mil"/> The GCV was required to have better protection than any vehicle in the military's inventory.<ref name="Industry day 1"/>

Army General [[Peter W. Chiarelli]] said that the "four main fundamentals" of the vehicle were: The ability to carry 12 soldiers and operate in all forms of combat; have significant protection; and deliver the first production vehicle by 2018.<ref name="$462 million">{{cite web|title=Fewer FCS Technologies for GCV Round Two|url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4787151&c=LAN&s=TOP|work=Defense News|access-date=23 September 2010|last=Brannen |first=Kate|date=22 September 2010}}{{dead link|date=August 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>

The IFV would be [[Modular design|modular]] and [[BCT Network|networked]] and offer improved survivability, mobility, and power management functions. The GCV family would use technologies pioneered with the IFV lead vehicle effort.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://defense-update.com/newscast/0909/news/220909_ground_combat_vehicle.html|title=U.S. Army Defines Ground Combat Vehicles (GCV) Priorities|work=Defense Update|access-date=March 29, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100316211643/http://defense-update.com/newscast/0909/news/220909_ground_combat_vehicle.html|archive-date=March 16, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref>

The Army's GCV requirements were left somewhat open-ended.<ref name="White">{{Cite web |last=White |first=Andrew |date=19 April 2010 |title=US Army delays GCV deadline |url=http://www.shephard.co.uk/news/landwarfareintl-com/us-army-delays-gcv-deadline/6155/ |access-date=19 April 2010 |website=Shephard |publisher=Shephard Group Limited |archive-date=28 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110428202826/http://www.shephard.co.uk/news/landwarfareintl-com/us-army-delays-gcv-deadline/6155/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

The GCV was to be networked and offer improved survivability. Elements of the Manned Ground Vehicles program were provided—such as the armor matrix—were provided to contractors to be utilized in design proposals for the GCV.<ref name="Lance & Shield"/>

===Network===
[[File:File-BCT Ground Combat Vehicle Program2.jpg|thumb|right|The GCV was planned to be networked.]]
The GCV was to be operable with the current ''battle command control and communications suite'' but would gradually use a more state-of-the-art networked integration system known as the [[BCT Network]]. It would provide exportable electrical power, and a battery charging capability for external hardware including vehicles and electronics from the [[BCT Soldier]] subsystems. The system would be capable of integration with unmanned systems and dismounted soldiers.<ref name="GCVspecs">{{Cite web |title=US Army Outlines Ground Combat Vehicles Priorities |url=http://defense-update.com/features/2010/january/gcv_army_details_100110.html |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100116124203/http://www.defense-update.com/features/2010/january/gcv_army_details_100110.html |archive-date=16 January 2010 |access-date=26 January 2010 |website=Defense Update |publisher=Lance & Shield}}</ref><ref name="Future Operational Concepts">{{Cite web |date=August 2010 |title=The Ground Combat Vehicle In the Conduct of Future Operational Concepts |url=http://www.bctmod.army.mil/GCV_focus/GCV%20CONOPS.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101011202739/http://www.bctmod.army.mil/GCV_focus/GCV%20CONOPS.pdf |archive-date=2010-10-11 |accessdate=17 August 2010}}</ref>

The Mounted Soldier System was to enhance situational awareness through wireless communications and input from vehicle sensors and external sources such as other vehicles.<ref name="MSS" />

=== Electrical power ===
The IFV would provide exportable electrical power, and battery charging capability for soldier systems.<ref name="GCVspecs"/>

===Mobility===
The GCV must have been transportable by cargo aircraft, rail, and ship. The Army required it to meet the availability rates of the current [[Stryker]]. The Army did not limit the vehicle by the dimensions of the [[C-130 Hercules]], which, in the past, constrained many designs. Air mobility would be provided by the more spacious [[C-17 Globemaster III]]. The GCV was to have good cross-country mobility, with a baseline requirement of 30&nbsp;mph off-road speed. The GCV should have delivered higher sustainability levels and consume less fuel than the Bradley or other vehicles of similar weight and power.<ref name="GCVspecs" /> The Army did not specify whether it preferred a tracked or wheeled solution, though the requirements seemed to suggest a tracked design was called for.<ref name="White"/><ref name="IFVspecs" />

In its standard configuration, the IFV would have a crew of three and carry a squad of nine. The vehicle could be reconfigured to support [[casualty evacuation]]. The Army stated no preference as to whether the IFV should be tracked or wheeled but suggested that it be tracked due to the weight stemming from the requirements.<ref name="IFVspecs">{{Cite web |last=Chavanne |first=Bettina |date=4 December 2009 |title=New Combat Vehicle for U.S. Army |url=http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story_channel.jsp?channel=defense&id=news%2FGCV120409.xml |website=Aviationweek |access-date=8 December 2009 |archive-date=29 April 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110429005938/http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story_channel.jsp?channel=defense&id=news%2FGCV120409.xml |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name="lighter">{{Cite web |last=Cox |first=Matthew |date=21 June 2010 |title=Casey: Make Ground Combat Vehicle lighter |url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2010/06/army_gcv_casey_062110w/ |access-date=16 August 2010 |work=Army Times}}</ref>

===Offensive capabilities===
The Army wanted the vehicle to feature a commander's weapons station, [[autocannon]], [[coaxial weapon]], and an [[anti-tank guided missile]] system. The weapons suite had to be manually operable when damaged and the commander's weapon station had to incorporate a shield.<ref name="Industry day 1">{{Cite web |last=Kash |first = MT |title=Industry day #1 |url=http://contracting.tacom.army.mil/majorsys/gcv/ID_1_Master_19Oct091.pptx |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110722183427/http://contracting.tacom.army.mil/majorsys/gcv/ID_1_Master_19Oct091.pptx |archive-date=22 July 2011 |access-date=19 September 2010 |df=dmy-all}}</ref> Additionally, a dismountable anti-armor weapon would be carried on board.<ref name="Industry day 1" /> The Army also stated that the weapon suite would emphasize modularity, be able to defeat other IFVs, and provide non-lethal capability to enable use in civilian environments.<ref name="GCVspecs"/><ref name="Optimizing"/>

The Army evaluated weapons solutions ranging from 25&nbsp;mm to 50&nbsp;mm caliber, and identified [[30mm caliber|30×173mm]] as "the most likely" design to meet the GCV's requirements. Specific requirements were for [[Airburst round|airburst]] capability to defeat infantry targets (with high explosive incendiary recognized as a "less effective alternative"), [[armor-piercing]] rounds to defeat material threats, and training ammunition for each tactical round. Potential candidates included five U.S. produced and three foreign-made rounds. In August 2013, a sources sought announcement was made for a [[Cooperative Research and Development Agreement]] for 30×173 mm ammunition: High Explosive Incendiary-Tracer (HEI-T), Armor Piercing Fin Stabilized Discarding Sabot-Tracer (APFSDS-T), and Target Practice Discarding Sabot-Tracer (TPDS-T). The announcement called for the cartridges to be compatible with the [[Bushmaster III]] weapon system, such as XM813 and/or [[Mk44 Bushmaster II|Mk 44 Mod 1]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gourley |first1=Scott R. |title=Army Refines 30mm Ammunition Efforts for GCV |url=https://www.defensemedianetwork.com/stories/army-refines-30mm-ammunition-efforts-for-gcv/ |access-date=10 January 2023 |work=Defense Media Network |date=18 August 2013 |archive-date=6 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230106230954/https://www.defensemedianetwork.com/stories/army-refines-30mm-ammunition-efforts-for-gcv/ |url-status=live }}</ref>

===Countermeasures===
The Army wanted the GCV to have a blast protection level equivalent to the [[MRAP]] and would utilize [[active protection system|hit avoidance systems]].<ref name="GCVspecs"/> The Army wanted to install an active protection system on the Ground Combat Vehicle. BAE tested the [[Artis LLC]] [[Iron Curtain (countermeasure)|Iron Curtain]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://dmilt.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7095:us-army-two-contenders-gear-up-for-gcv-active-protection-&catid=37:north-america&Itemid=59 |title=US Army; Two contenders gear up for GCV active protection |publisher=Defence Market Intelligence |date=June 24, 2013 |accessdate=2015-01-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020063524/http://dmilt.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7095:us-army-two-contenders-gear-up-for-gcv-active-protection-&catid=37:north-america&Itemid=59 |archive-date=October 20, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and General Dynamics demonstrated a version of the Israeli [[Trophy (countermeasure)|Trophy]] system.<ref>[https://archive.today/20131019160125/http://www.defensenews.com/article/20131015/DEFREG02/310150018/US-Israeli-Team-Demo-APS-Canada US-Israeli Team To Demo APS for Canada] - Defensenews.com, 15 October 2013</ref> By incorporating an APS, the GCV would only need 18 tons of ballistic armor protection, compared to 52 tons of armor required without it. Developers were considering modular armor technology, with the ability to add on and remove armor plates depending on threat levels and mission requirements.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Osborn |first1=Kris |title=Army Looks Beyond Armor to Upgrade Vehicle Fleet |url=https://www.military.com/daily-news/2013/10/30/army-looks-beyond-armor-to-upgrade-vehicle-fleet.html?ESRC=todayinmil.sm |access-date=10 January 2023 |work=Military.com |date=30 October 2013 |archive-date=10 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230110003233/https://www.military.com/daily-news/2013/10/30/army-looks-beyond-armor-to-upgrade-vehicle-fleet.html?ESRC=todayinmil.sm |url-status=live }}</ref>

The [[Mounted Soldier System]] (MSS) was being developed for GCV crew members.<ref name="Industry day 1" /><ref name="MSS">{{Cite web |date=May 2010 |title=Mounted Soldier System (MSS) |url=https://peosoldier.army.mil/FactSheets/PMSWAR/SWAR_MSS_MSS.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/5sDUDTRYy?url=https://peosoldier.army.mil/FactSheets/PMSWAR/SWAR_MSS_MSS.pdf |archive-date=2010-08-24 |access-date=9 August 2010}}</ref> Dismounted leaders would utilize the Ground Soldier Systems.<ref name="Industry day 1" />

Thermal management and acoustic noise reduction would be utilized to avoid detection. The vehicle would be able to avoid threats by laying [[Smoke screen|obscurants]]. An array of hit avoidance systems would be leveraged and the Army offered the various active protection systems developed for the Manned Ground Vehicle program.<ref name="Industry day 1" /> The GCV enabled the detection and neutralization of mines at standoff ranges.<ref name="mine neutalizer">{{cite web|title=Towards a Comprehensive Vehicle Strategy|url=http://www.dtic.mil/ndia/2009combatvehicle/GeneralVane.pdf|date=13 October 2009|access-date=20 September 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120927173742/http://www.dtic.mil/ndia/2009combatvehicle/GeneralVane.pdf|archive-date=27 September 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> The vehicle was to be equipped with an engagement detection system. The Army required the IFV to have the passive blast protection level equal to the [[MRAP (armored vehicle)|MRAP]].<ref name="GCVspecs"/>

The Army made available the composition of the armor of the Manned Ground Vehicle program. A [[transparent armor]] shield would provide protection for the vehicle commander when exposed through the turret. In addition, a Vehicle Health Management System would provide vehicle diagnostic monitoring systems for commanders. A fire suppression system and ammunition detonation protection would be utilized for damage control.<ref name="Industry day 1" />

A secondary squad egress was to be provided for the squad to exit in emergencies.<ref name="Industry day 1" />

== Tactics ==
The Infantry Fighting Vehicle variant was intended to fill the infantry transport role in [[Brigade Combat Team#Heavy brigade combat team|Heavy Brigade Combat Teams]] replacing the aging M2 Bradley.<ref name="Optimizing" />

In the U.S. Army, as part of the ongoing restructuring, [[Brigade Combat Team#Heavy brigade combat team|Heavy Brigade Combat Team]] Brigades would have 62 IFV's, [[battalion]]s would have 29, and [[platoon]]s would have 4.<ref name="Future Operational Concepts" /><ref name="GCV PROGRAM PLAN">{{Cite web |date=29 January 2010 |title=GCV PROGRAM PLAN |url=http://contracting.tacom.army.mil/majorsys/gcv/attach/Attch%200008_GCV%20Program%20Schedule.pdf |access-date=5 August 2010}}{{dead link|date=April 2025|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Platoons were to be led by platoon leader GCV which would be accompanied by platoon medic, [[Artillery observer|forward observer]], Radio Transmission Operator, and other attachments and would command three other GCVs.<ref name="Future Operational Concepts" />

The Army placed importance on the GCV's ability to carry a full nine-man squad. Numerous Army studies have concluded that a squad, made up of two [[fireteam]]s, should be composed of nine to eleven soldiers. The M2 Bradley cannot carry a complete squad from one vehicle, creating risk when transitioning from mounted to dismounted operations. The Bradley's lower carrying capacity was accepted for greater (than previous vehicles) mounted lethality and cost savings, leading to squads being broken apart for transport. A GCV with a nine-man squad would have allowed the squad leader to control and communicate with the squad while mounted, simplify the transition to dismounted operations in complex terrain, and allow the squad to conduct independent fire and maneuver immediately upon dismount. Replacing the Bradley on a one-for-one basis would have four GCVs per mechanized infantry platoon carrying one full nine-man squad in a single vehicle, with three vehicles carrying squads and one carrying the platoon's organic and attached enablers.<ref>{{cite report |last1=Held |first1=Bruce |last2=Lorell |first2=Mark A. |last3=Quinlivan |first3=James T. |last4=Chad C. |first4=Serena |title=Understanding Why a Ground Combat Vehicle That Carries Nine Dismounts Is Important to the Army |url=https://www.rand.org/pubs/research_reports/RR184.html |publisher=Rand Corporation |year=2013 |access-date=10 January 2023 |archive-date=10 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230110001910/https://www.rand.org/pubs/research_reports/RR184.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

==Variants==
[[File:GCV Infantry Fighting Vehicle.jpg|thumb|right|A notional GCV]]

The Army was using an incremental approach to combat vehicle modernization, centered on the Ground Combat Vehicle. The deployment was to be synchronized with upgrades, reset, and divestiture of existing vehicles. Vehicles displaced by the IFV may then replace selected [[Variants of the M113 armored personnel carrier|M113 family of vehicles]] such as [[command and control]], medical evacuation, and mortar carrier, allowing the Army to begin divestiture of the M113 family of vehicles. Upgrades to existing [[Bradley Fighting Vehicle|Bradley]] and Stryker vehicles may have been considered as risk mitigation based on the rate at which the GCV was introduced.<ref name="Optimizing"/><ref name="Details">{{Cite web |last=Cox |first=Matthew |date=10 September 2009 |title=U.S. Army Details Ground Combat Vehicle Plans |url=http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=4271063&c=AME&s=LAN |access-date=13 December 2009 |website=[[Defense News]] }}{{dead link|date=August 2021|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Although upgraded, the Bradley and Stryker would also be replaced in the midterm.<ref name=Optimizing/>

===Infantry fighting vehicle===
The infantry fighting vehicle variant replaced the previous infantry carrier replacement effort, the XM1206 Infantry Carrier Vehicle of the FCS MGV program.<ref name="replace">{{Cite web |date=21 July 2009 |title=Army Partially Terminates FCS Manned Ground Vehicle |url=http://www.asdnews.com/news/21975/Army_Partially_Terminates_FCS_Manned_Ground_Vehicle.htm |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110501092632/http://www.asdnews.com/news/21975/Army_Partially_Terminates_FCS_Manned_Ground_Vehicle.htm |archive-date=1 May 2011 |access-date=27 January 2010 |website=ASD News}}</ref> The IFV was to hold a crew of three and a squad of nine.<ref name=IFVspecs/>

== Competitors ==
;Competitors
There were four known competing contractors for the Ground Combat Vehicle contract.

[[File:BAE Northrop GCV.jpg|thumb|right|A concept image of a BAE contender]]
*BAE Systems, Northrop Grumman, QinetiQ and Saft Group were working jointly on development.<ref>{{cite web|work=BusinessWeek|url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9E62TB00.htm|title=BAE, Northrop to develop new ground combat vehicle|agency=The Associated Press|date=March 1, 2010|accessdate=|archive-date=30 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130165545/http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9E62TB00.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref> The program was managed by Mark Signorelli.<ref name="BAE 1">{{cite web|title=BAE Offers Hybrid-Electric Combat Vehicle|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/defense/2010/06/bae-offers-hybridelectric.php|publisher=National Journal Group Inc|accessdate=18 June 2010|author=Sydney J. Freedberg Jr.}} {{dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name="BAE Businessweek">{{cite web|title=BAE, Northrop expand team to bid on Army contract|url=http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9H6UDBO2.htm|publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|accessdate=27 July 2010|date=26 July 2010|archive-date=25 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121025225229/http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9H6UDBO2.htm|url-status=dead}}</ref> The team believed it could field the vehicle up to two years sooner than projected.<ref name=ausa /> Development cost were "tens of millions of dollars".<ref name="GCV reform 2">{{cite web|title=Army sees new rules for combat vehicles soon|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE69L55W20101022|publisher=Thomson Reuters|accessdate=23 October 2010|author=Andrea Shalal-Esa|date=22 October 2010|archive-date=25 October 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101025052846/http://www.reuters.com/article/idUSTRE69L55W20101022|url-status=live}}</ref>

:*'''Work breakdown'''<ref name="BAE Businessweek" />
::*BAE would provide general vehicle design, [[program management]], integration of the vehicle components.
::*Northrop Grumman would provide technology pertaining to command, control, communications, intelligence, surveillance and reconnaissance.
::*QinetiQ would provide the electric drive propulsion system.
::*Saft would provide the energy storage system.

:*'''Features'''
::*Tracked with an E-X-Drive hybrid-electric engine.<ref name="BAE Businessweek" />
::*Baseline weight of 53 tons with a weight tolerance of 75 tons for modular armor.<ref name="BAE GCV">{{cite web|title=Firm wants Army to use hybrid technology on GCV|url=http://www.armytimes.com/news/2010/07/army_gcv_hybrid_electric_072610w/|work=Army Times |access-date=27 July 2010|last=Brannen |first=Kate|date=26 July 2010}}</ref>
::*Manned turret.<ref name="BAE GCV" />
::*Leveraged a [[V-hull]] and Hard-Kill and Soft-Kill active protection systems.<ref name="BAE shape">{{cite web|title=BAE-Northrop GCV Hybrid Drive A Gamble|url=http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story_channel.jsp?channel=defense&id=news/asd/2010/07/28/06.xml&headline=BAE-Northrop%20GCV%20Hybrid%20Drive%20A%20Gamble|publisher=The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc|access-date=28 July 2010|author=Michael Fabey|date=28 July 2010}}{{dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref name="BAE’s GCV">{{cite web|title=BAE's GCV Weighs 53 Tons, Hybrid|publisher=Military Advantage|author=Colin Clark|date=28 July 2010|url=https://www.military.com/dodbuzz/2010/07/28/baes-gcv-weighs-53-tons-hybrid|access-date=6 January 2023|archive-date=6 January 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230106214726/https://www.military.com/dodbuzz/2010/07/28/baes-gcv-weighs-53-tons-hybrid|url-status=live}}</ref>
::*Wider and taller than a Bradley. All or most of the storage was internal accounting for the extra size.<ref name="BAE shape" />

*[[General Dynamics Land Systems]], [[Lockheed Martin]], [[Detroit Diesel]] and [[Raytheon]] were working jointly on development.<ref name="General Dynamics">{{cite press release|title=General Dynamics Team Submits Army Ground Combat Vehicle Proposal|url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/general-dynamics-team-submits-army-ground-combat-vehicle-proposal-94578069.html|work=PR Newswire|access-date=21 May 2010|archive-date=24 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100524080009/http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/general-dynamics-team-submits-army-ground-combat-vehicle-proposal-94578069.html|url-status=live}}</ref>

:*'''Work breakdown'''<ref name="General Dynamics" />
::*General Dynamics Land Systems led the team as systems integrator and was responsible for soldier interfaces and chassis.
::*Lockheed Martin would develop the turret and weaponry.
::*Detroit Diesel would develop the propulsion system.
::*Raytheon would develop the active protection systems, sensors.

:*'''Features'''
::*Used conventional diesel.<ref name="BAE 1" />
