:*'''Work breakdown'''<ref name="PUMA" />
::*SAIC would lead the team as project manager.
::*Boeing would supply the weaponry.
::*Both Krauss-Maffei and Rheinmetall's roles were unknown.

:*'''Features'''
::*Larger, reconfigured Puma chassis.<ref name="PUMA" />
::*Used conventional diesel and a six-road-wheel configuration.<ref name="BAE 1" />
*Advanced Defense Vehicle Systems (ADVS) submitted its wheeled proposal which was rejected for being non-compliant. ADVS protested the decision, but withdrew it after the Army canceled the RfP.<ref name="ADVS"/><ref name="Crains resubmit"/>

:*'''Features'''
::*Wheeled.<ref>{{cite web|title=Michigan Company Protests Rejection Of Its Wheeled GCV Bid|url=https://defensenewsstand.com/Inside-the-Army/Inside-the-Army-06/28/2010/menu-id-288.html|publisher=Inside Washington Publishers|access-date=6 August 2010|date=June 28, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709010646/https://defensenewsstand.com/Inside-the-Army/Inside-the-Army-06/28/2010/menu-id-288.html|archive-date=2011-07-09|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===BAE Systems===
The BAE Systems GCV design had a steel-core hull and an integrated electronic network capability with embedded intelligence, surveillance, and reconnaissance equipment. Its turret was unmanned. The centerpiece of the vehicle was its simplified drive train. It was propelled by a [[hybrid electric drive]] (HED), which was developed by Northrop Grumman, that produced 1,100&nbsp;kW of electricity. Advantages to it are fewer components and lower volume and weight compared to current power plants. The transmission was 40 percent smaller and the drive train had half the moving parts. The hybrid drive train cost 5 percent more than a mechanical system, but had a 20 percent reduction in life-cycle cost. The electric drive allows for smoother low-speed operation and less noise. The vehicle burned 20 percent less fuel while running, with {{convert|4.61|USgal|liter|abbr=off|sp=us}} per hour used while stationary. It had a top speed of {{convert|43|mph|km/h|abbr=on}}, could go from 0 to {{convert|20|mph|km/h|abbr=on}} in 7.8 seconds, and had a range of {{convert|186|mi|km|abbr=on}} with a 255-gallon fuel capacity. Disadvantages to the BAE design included a weight of 70 tons and fuel efficiency of 0.73 mpg.<ref name="BAE"/><ref>[http://www.gizmag.com/bae-gcv-hybrid-tank/25113/ BAE Systems releases details of hybrid tank] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160727011809/http://www.gizmag.com/bae-gcv-hybrid-tank/25113/ |date=27 July 2016 }} - Gizmag.com, November 22, 2012</ref> BAE integrated the [[Artis, LLC|Artis]] Iron Curtain active protection system to defeat incoming rockets and missiles before they can hit the vehicle. The Army conducted tests on the system in April 2013, and it successfully passed all tests.<ref>{{Cite web |date=April 29, 2013 |title=Iron Curtain Successful in Firing Tests |url=http://defense-update.com/20130429_iron-curtain-tested.html |publisher=Defense Update |access-date=2013-05-08 |archive-date=18 May 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220518120741/https://defense-update.com/20130429_iron-curtain-tested.html |url-status=live }}</ref> BAE tested a system for the vehicle to drive in low visibility conditions using a [[Humvee]] with blacked out windows as a surrogate.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Insinna |first1=Valerie |title=Undeterred By Possible Delays, BAE Continues Ground Combat Vehicle Development |url=https://www.nationaldefensemagazine.org/articles/2013/8/28/undeterred-by-possible-delays-bae-continues-ground-combat-vehicle-development |access-date=11 January 2023 |work=National Defense |publisher=National Defense Industrial Association |date=28 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150518091246/http://www.nationaldefensemagazine.org/blog/Lists/Posts/Post.aspx?ID=1245 |archive-date=18 May 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> In August 2013, the BAE GCV's hybrid electric drive completed 2,000 miles of testing on a fully integrated stationary test stand.<ref>{{cite news |title=BAE Systems Ground Combat Vehicle Hybrid Electric Drive successfully completed 2000 miles testing |url=https://www.armyrecognition.com/august_2013_defense_industry_military_army_news_uk/bae_systems_ground_combat_vehicle_hybrid_electric_drive_successfully_completed_2000_miles_testing.html |access-date=11 January 2023 |work=Army Recognition |date=27 August 2013 |archive-date=11 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230111034244/https://www.armyrecognition.com/august_2013_defense_industry_military_army_news_uk/bae_systems_ground_combat_vehicle_hybrid_electric_drive_successfully_completed_2000_miles_testing.html |url-status=live }}</ref>

Although dramatic funding cuts for the GCV program in January 2014 put the very completion of the acquisition effort in jeopardy, funding remained for research on a hybrid-electric propulsion system. The BAE GCV's hybrid-electric engine is more fuel efficient, has fewer moving parts, and has faster acceleration than ordinary engines. While powering a vehicle concept that reached 70 tons proved impractical, its benefits of providing power for onboard electronics, silent overwatch, and short, stealthy movements are still promising. BAE has pledged to support future Army developmental efforts with technologies from their GCV entry.<ref>{{cite news |title=Hopes Dim for BAE's 'Green' Combat Vehicle |url=https://www.military.com/dodbuzz/2014/01/22/hopes-dim-for-baes-green-combat-vehicle |access-date=10 January 2023 |work=Military.com |date=22 January 2014 |archive-date=10 January 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230110024129/https://www.military.com/dodbuzz/2014/01/22/hopes-dim-for-baes-green-combat-vehicle |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2014, BAE Systems was awarded a $7.9 million study contract for technical, cost, and risk assessments to utilize the GCV TD phase integrated hybrid-electric propulsion and mobility subsystems Automotive Test Rig (ATR) and the hybrid-electric integrated propulsion subsystem (Hotbuck) for the Future Fighting Vehicle (FFV) effort.<ref name="auto1">[http://www.defensemedianetwork.com/stories/army-attempts-to-salvage-gcv-technology-advances/ Army Attempts to Salvage GCV Technology Advances] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403113200/http://www.defensemedianetwork.com/stories/army-attempts-to-salvage-gcv-technology-advances/ |date=3 April 2015 }} - Defensemedianetwork.com, 25 July 2014</ref><ref name="auto">[http://www.militaryaerospace.com/articles/2014/08/gcv-ffv-technologies.html Army asks BAE Systems and General Dynamics to recycle GCV vetronics for Future Fighting Vehicle] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820095142/http://www.militaryaerospace.com/articles/2014/08/gcv-ffv-technologies.html |date=20 August 2014 }} - Militaryaerospace.com, 18 August 2014</ref>

===General Dynamics===
In October 2013, General Dynamics successfully completed a preliminary design review of their GCV design. Subsystem and component design reviews were held from August to October of that year and led to the four-day PDR. General Dynamics demonstrated their vehicle met Tier 1 affordability, reliability, and other requirements. The success of the PDR meant that the General Dynamics GCV IFV could be expected to be operationally effective and suitable.<ref>[https://archive.today/20131109162004/http://www.armyrecognition.com/november_2013_defense_industry_military_news_uk/general_dynamics_completed_preliminary_design_revuiew_of_gcv_ground_combat_vehicle_design_0911132.html General Dynamics completed Preliminary Design Review of Ground Combat Vehicle design] - Armyrecognition.com, 9 November 2013</ref>

===SAIC–Boeing===
Reports suggest that the SAIC–Boeing GCV proposal was rejected by the Army primarily due to concerns over the proposed vehicle's survivability. The Army's primary concern appeared to have been the vehicle's proposed active protection system and the underbody armor designed to protect crewmembers from IEDs. As part of GAO's examination of the protest, it was noted that the Army identified 20 significant weaknesses and informed SAIC that it was "of utmost importance" for the firm to address them.{{sfn|Feickert|2014|p=12}}

While SAIC and the German MOD offered potential solutions, the Army judged these as inadequate to address its concerns. There were also additional Army concerns—such as insufficient head clearance for crew members, problems with vehicle occupant seating, a risk of toxic fumes in the crew compartment due to battery pack location, and various hazards affecting a soldier's ability to exit the rear of the GCV—that played a role in GAO's denial of SAIC's protest.{{sfn|Feickert|2014|p=12}}

